edu.umd.cs.datastructures.projectskeletons.kdtree

Class BoundedPriorityQueue<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.umd.cs.datastructures.projectskeletons.kdtree.BoundedPriorityQueue<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - An Object that will be held by this. Note that T is not declared as Comparable: its priority is supplied on the fly by the enqueueing method.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>

    public class BoundedPriorityQueue<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<T>

    BoundedPriorityQueue is a Priority Queue whose number of elements is bounded. Insertions are such that if the queue's provided capacity is surpassed, its length is not expanded, but rather the maximum priority element is ejected (which could be the element just attempted to be enqueued). Note that BoundedPriorityQueues are Iterables.

    • Method Detail

      • enqueue

        public void enqueue(T element,
                    double priority)
        Enqueueing elements for BoundedPriorityQueues works a little bit differently from general case PriorityQueue objects. If the queue is not at capacity, the element is inserted at its appropriate location in the sequence. On the other hand, if the object is at capacity, the element is inserted in its appropriate spot in the sequence (if such a spot exists, based on its priority) and the maximum priority element is ejected from the structure.
        Parameters:
        element - The element to insert in the queue.
        priority - The priority of the element to insert in the queue.
        See Also:
        dequeue()

      • last

        public T last()
        Returns the last element in the queue. Useful for cases where we want to compare the priorities of a given quantity with the maximum priority of our stored quantities. In a linked minheap-based implementation of any PriorityQueue, this operation would scan O(n) nodes and O(nlogn) links. In an array-based minheap, it takes constant time.
        Returns:
        The maximum priority element in our queue, or null if the queue is empty.

      • iterator

        public java.util.Iterator<T> iterator()
